Ars Praefectus
et Subscriptor
Tribus: Space Battleship Yamato
Registered: Jul 4, 2001Posts: 4287
Posted: Fri Jul 26, 2013 3:36 am
secretknight42 wrote:Well, because of bad (but wonderfully delicious) choices over the last two months, I’m up 10lb, now at around 215. Hopefully, now that I’m on a mission to lose what I’ve gained, I will drop those 10 quickly, and continue past 205, where I’ve been stuck for some time.Here are two questions since there are knowledgeable people in the thread:1. I do about one hour of cardio a day. Would it be helpful to get any of those protein shakes or whatever to drink after that hour? Would there be any benefits for my goal, which is dropping weight? Or, should I just stick with water?Some people say always refuel after cardio, some people say wait awhile for optimum calorie burn. What I do is just go by feel. If I feel my workout that day was exceptionally rough, and my body is broken down, then I refuel right away, and be sure to eat a hearty meal afterwards. If I feel my workout was decent, but not too tough, and I'm not hungry, I tend to just let it go, and eat whenever my next meal is. Case in point, Monday I had a horrendous 12 mile run. I was overheating, undernourished (poor prep by me), and cramping up. After that, I made sure to pound a protein drink, and eat a giant (but healthy!) dinner soon afterwards. Today, I had a great 12 mile run. I finished relatively fresh, still with some gas in the tank, my body feels good. It's been 3 hours since my run finished, and I'm about ready to make dinner now.secretknight42 wrote:2. May be unrelated to the topic of the thread. Does anyone have suggestions about vitamin supplements for men? I figure since I am trying to take better care of myself, I may as well look into it. Also, a body that is getting everything that it needs may be more amicable to losing fat (well, it makes sense in my head).In a previous life, I used to take tons of stuff. All kinds of stuff. When I started running I just used a multivitamin and occasionally some random stuff like a B complex, zinc, etc. Eventually through forgetfulness, I now take nothing. I feel no different. For some people, a multivitamin, and certain supplements make a real difference in how they feel, but it doesn't have an effect on me. I regulate my portion sizes, but I still eat all kinds of stuff so I might be meeting my body's random nutritional needs that way.The unfortunate fact is that no one can tell you what you have to do to lose weight faster, other than watch what you eat (for whatever diet you're following), control your portion sizes, and get out there and break a sweat. Those are the only universal truths. My advice on the cardio + supplements, is do the cardio first, and get used to that. Once you're in the rhythm of constant workouts, and you know your body and it's performance characteristics, then add in one thing at a time. If after a few months, you throw in a B complex and all of a sudden you're 10% faster, then congratulations! You found something that works for you. If you you do everything all at once, then there's too many variables, and you don't know what's really working for you. Is it the vitmain? Is it the protein drink? Is it just the cardio and you don't need any of that? Some people get lucky and find the perfect combination of things for THEIR body right off the bat. The rest of us have to stumble around and experiment. You are a mythbuster for your own body.
