secretknight42 wrote:1. I do about one hour of cardio a day. Would it be helpful to get any of those protein shakes or whatever to drink after that hour? Would there be any benefits for my goal, which is dropping weight? Or, should I just stick with water?Zanshin pretty much nailed it. They aren't necessary and are basically excess calories. If you don't need them, don't use them, and if you do use them try not to get dependent on them.Quote:2. May be unrelated to the topic of the thread. Does anyone have suggestions about vitamin supplements for men? I figure since I am trying to take better care of myself, I may as well look into it. Also, a body that is getting everything that it needs may be more amicable to losing fat (well, it makes sense in my head).To answer this question you should probably get some bloodwork done. If you have insurance and it covers well visits, go to your doctor's office ask for a complete blood workup. If anything is low supplement to bring it back in line. While you're supplementing, find out what's deficient in your diet/lifestyle and work to correct it so that when you're done supplementing you don't go deficient again.
